Many researchers have developed mathematical models to study the transmission of HIV at either the CD4+ T-cell level (see, e.g., [3, 4, 7, 29–33]) or at the population level (see, e.g., [25, 26, 34, 35]). In the present research, we study a model for transmission of HIV at the population level originally proposed by Roberts and Saha [25] as a general epidemic model, and later developed by Ding et al. [26] as a stochastic differential equation model for the progression to AIDS in a population infected with HIV. The nonlinear, logistic-type, differential equation model discussed by Ding et al. is as follows (see also [35]): 1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
